<TITLE> Seventh person charged in Rhys Jones inquiry </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, April 18 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A seventh person has been charged in connection with the death of Liverpool schoolboy Rhys Jones. James Yates, 20, from the Croxteth part of the city, was charged with assisting an offender and is due to appear before Liverpool magistrates on Friday. On Thursday, a 17-year-old youth was remanded in custody, charged with the boy's murder. The 11-year-old was shot in the neck in Croxteth last August after returning from football practice. Police have also charged three youths, aged 15, 16 and 17, and two men, Melvyn Coy, 24 and Gary Kayes, 25, with assisting an offender. The 16-year-old was also charged with possession of a firearm. None of the youths can be named for legal reasons. Three people aged 49, 50 and 54 as well as a 16-year-old have been released on bail pending further inquiries. A 21-year-old woman was released without charg
